# Vercel Web Analytics Implementation

Successfully implemented Vercel Web Analytics for this Next.js project following the latest official documentation.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/analytics` version 2.0.1 using npm
- Added package to dependencies in `package.json`
- Created `package-lock.json` for dependency management

### 2. Analytics Integration (app/layout.tsx)
- Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from '@vercel/analytics/next';`
- Added `<Analytics />` component to the root layout's body section
- Placed after the `<Providers>` component to ensure proper initialization

### 3. Files Modified
- `app/layout.tsx` - Added Analytics import and component
- `package.json` - Added @vercel/analytics dependency

### 4. Files Created
- `package-lock.json` - Generated by npm during package installation

## Implementation Details

The implementation follows the official Vercel Analytics quickstart guide for Next.js App Router projects. The Analytics component was added to the root layout file (`app/layout.tsx`), which is the recommended approach for Next.js 14 with the App Router.

The component will automatically:
- Track page views across all routes
- Collect visitor data
- Send analytics data to Vercel's infrastructure

## Build Verification

- ✅ Next.js compilation succeeded without errors
- ✅ TypeScript types are valid
- ✅ No syntax errors introduced
- ⚠️ Build encountered expected database connection error (unrelated to this change)

## Next Steps for Deployment

To complete the setup:
1. Deploy the application to Vercel
2. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel Dashboard:
   - Navigate to your project's Analytics section
   - Click the "Enable" button
3. Analytics tracking will automatically begin after the next deployment

The tracking script will be served from `/_vercel/insights/*` routes.

## Notes

- Used npm with `--legacy-peer-deps` flag due to existing peer dependency conflicts in the project (unrelated to Analytics)
- All changes preserve existing code structure and functionality
- The Analytics component is lightweight and has no performance impact
